                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#_ων"><seg part="F">ων</seg></name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#_λας"><seg part="F">λας</seg></name></persName>
                    <lb n="2a"/><space extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>ôn, <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>las.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>on, <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>las.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>on, <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>las.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>The two preserved endings are probably vestiges of two men's names at the nominative case. The <foreign rend="italic">vacat</foreign> below 
               shows either that this was the end of a longer list or that only those two men were mentioned. However there would be no room for fathers' names,
               which are usually mentioned. Another faint possibility for line 1 would be the ending of a participle such as <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἱαριτεύων</foreign>,
               but the word order would be somewhat surprising. The whole remains rather unclear.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
